When instantiating the `RemootioClient` class, a lot of steps happens:
1. a connection is established to the device;
2. the [authentication](https://github.com/remootio/remootio-api-documentation/blob/master/websocket_api_v3_specification.md#7-auth-frame-and-the-authentication-flow) takes place (whereby the current status of the device is also found out);
3. a [HELLO frame](https://github.com/remootio/remootio-api-documentation/blob/master/websocket_api_v3_specification.md#hello-frame) is sent to the device and the response is awaited to find out the serial number of the device and the API version used by the device;
4. two asynchronous tasks are started to send [PING frames](https://github.com/remootio/remootio-api-documentation/blob/master/websocket_api_v3_specification.md#ping-frame) to the device and to receive and handle frames from the device.

The whole of the above initialization process takes place partly asynchronously and is encompassed by a [`Lock`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio-sync.html#asyncio.Lock). When the (asynchronous) property `initialized` is queried, it is queried whether this `Lock` is active, and if so, the unlocking of it is awaited and only then the value of the property is returned.

